  "doc_id": "14502",
  "text": "We have recently shown that high-density lipoproteins (HDL) augment ischemia driven angiogenesis in vivo and in vitro [CITATION_1] . These effects in vitro were mediated via a stabilization of HIF-1α [CITATION_2] and an elevation in VEGF [CITATION_3] . We have also recently identified that reconstituted HDL (rHDL) rescues diabetes-impaired neovascularization [CITATION_4] . Given the distinct mechanistic similarities between the impairment of angiogenesis in diabetes and in aging, we now seek to determine if rHDL can also improve age-impaired angiogenesis. We investigated this using two surgical murine models of wound healing and hindlimb ischemia and find that rHDL augments wound closure and hindlimb angiogenesis in aged mice. Clinical trials that have raised HDL in patients with advanced atheroma have been disappointing showing no benefit on advanced plaque size, which may be related to the age-induced failure of HDL function in the context of advanced atherosclerosis and aging. Our studies highlight an alternate therapeutic use of HDL for angiogenesis-related diseases that is effective in the context of aging, which may facilitate its eventual successful translation in clinic.",
